["translation-strain","critique-mode","teaching-seed","modern-human-condition","digital-comparison","loneliness"]},"practice_candidate":{"title":"Test the Borrowed Word","practice_line":"Before using a spiritual word about yourself, test what it changes today.","purpose":"To stop inherited or online spiritual language from hiding avoidance, self-erasure, superiority, withdrawal, or vague identity performance.","target_human_problem":"Digital comparison, loneliness, withdrawal, and meaning loss caused by adopting impressive language without a matching practice.","target_cohort":"Adults who frequently use spiritual, therapeutic, or philosophical terms to explain their identity, relationships, work, or suffering.","non_fit":"Not for people in acute crisis, active addiction withdrawal, psychosis, severe depression, or situations where ordinary clinical, legal, or interpersonal help is urgently needed. Not useful when the person is already practicing under skilled guidance with clear feedback.","duration":"10 minutes","frequency":"Three times in one week when a charged spiritual word appears in thought, journaling, posting, or conversation.","minimum_attempt":"Use the practice on three different words or three different uses of one word before judging it.","steps":["Write the word you are using, such as detachment, surrender, emptiness, humility, calling, witness, or service.","Name the situation where you want to use it.","Write what the word asks you to do in the next 24 hours.","Write what it might let you avoid doing.","Name who could be helped or harmed if you act from this word.","Choose one small action that would make the word accountable, such as apologizing, resting, asking directly, finishing a task, seeking help, or staying silent.","After the action, write whether the word made you clearer, kinder, more avoidant, more grandiose, or more numb."],"notice":["Whether the word produces a concrete act or only a self-image.","Whether the word increases contact with