mptiness, witness, humility, and service through source role plus receiver wound should report fewer cases where a noble word hides avoidance, self-erasure, or isolation. If ordinary journaling works as well or better, the model is weakened.","If receiver-wound strain matters, then the same borrowed term should produce different risks in different cohorts: detachment should skew toward withdrawal in isolated people and toward discipline in overattached but well-supported people. If cohort differences do not appear, the receiver field is weak.","Close-read Chinese Buddhist matching-concepts cases where Daoist terms were used to translate Buddhist ideas, especially non-being and emptiness, to test whether historical translation strain predicts later doctrinal correction.","Protocol improvement: before using an inherited spiritual word in a teaching, ask what practice trained it, what authority corrected it, what modern wound might distort it, and what behavior would show that distortion."],"teaching_candidate":{"title":"Test the Word","teaching_line":"Do not use a borrowed word until you know what it asks of you.","doctrine_claim":"A teaching remains responsible only when its inherited word, practice role, authority, verification method, and target human wound still fit together.","body":"A serious word should change a real act. Before you call something detachment, surrender, emptiness, calling, humility, or service, ask what it asks you to do today. If the word makes you less truthful, less caring, less able to repair harm, or less open to correction, it has lost its discipline. Keep the word only where it makes attention and conduct clearer.","target_human_problem":"Loneliness, digital comparison, withdrawal, and meaning loss intensified by impressive language that hides avoidance or self-display.","target_cohort":"Reflective adults and older teens with support who move between spiritual, therapeutic, philosophical, online, or religious vocabularies and use them to