situation where you want to use it.","Write what the word asks you to do in the next 24 hours.","Write what the word might let you avoid doing.","Name the person, promise, task, or relationship that could be helped or harmed if you act from this word.","Choose one small accountable action: apologize, rest, ask directly, finish a task, seek help, stop posting, or stay present without performing insight.","After the action, write whether the word made you clearer, kinder, more avoidant, more grandiose, or more numb."],"notice":["Whether the word produces a concrete act or only a self-image.","Whether the word increases contact with people and duties or protects you from correction.","Whether the word makes you more available to reality or more hidden from it."],"caution":"Stop if the practice increases shame, panic, dissociation, compulsive confession, self-punishment, or obsessive checking. This is not a substitute for clinical, legal, or relational help.","weakens_if":"The practice weakens if repeated use produces more rumination, less action, less care for others, or no better distinction between insight and avoidance than ordinary journaling.","risk_level":"low","status":"seed","tags":["translation-strain","borrowed-language","attention-practice","digital-comparison","loneliness","meaning-loss"]},"tests":[{"title":"Prior Art Difference Check","test_type":"prior-art","target_type":"idea","prediction":"Close prior art should cover comparison, functional equivalence, and speech role, but should not usually require every doctrine candidate to test both source-side carriers and receiver-wound misuse before teaching.","result":"Pending. Initial search found strong overlap with Smith, Freiberger, Panikkar, speech-act theory, and religious-language analysis, so novelty should remain moderate unless the receiver-wound field adds predictive value.","impact":"pending","next_action":"Compare the proposed fields against comparative theology, speech-act theory, Asad-style discursive tradition, Sharf-style experience critique, and meditation-safety literature.","status":"proposed"},{"title":"Receiver Wound Practice Pilot","test_type":"practice-report","target_type":"practice","prediction":"Participants using the Word Carry Test should identify more concrete cases where a noble word hides avoidance, isolation, self-display, or self-erasure than participants using ordinary reflective journaling.","result":"Pending practitioner reports.","impact":"pending","next_action":"Run a small screened journaling pilot with pre/post examples of charged words and code changes in action clarity, repair, isolation, and rumination.","status":"proposed"},{"title":"Dual Trained Practitioner Challenge","test_type":"falsification-attempt","target_type":"idea","prediction":"If the model is too analytic, dual-trained practitioners will say receiver-wound checks add little beyond existing teacher correction, community practice, or common discernment. If they can name concrete misuses the check would prevent, the model strengthens.","result":"Pending interviews.","impact":"pending","next_action":"Interview practitioners trained in at least two traditions, including Buddhist and Advaita teachers, Christian spiritual directors, Zen or Chan teachers, and contemplative-experience researchers.","status":"proposed"},{"title":"Comparative Law Transfer Test","test_type":"cross-domain","target_type":"idea","prediction":"Legal concepts with similar names should fail in transplant more often when receiver-side institutional wounds, incentives, and authority structures counterfeit the source role. If shared terms predict implementation success just as well, the receiver-wound model loses cross-domain force.","result":"Pending.","impact":"pending","next_action":"Score due process, trust, equity, and rights across legal systems by source role, receiver institution, authority, verification, and misuse risk before comparing implementation outcomes.","status":"proposed"},{"title":"Rumination Safety Check","test_type":"safety","target_type":"practice","prediction":"For the named cohort, the practice should reduce vague identity language without increasing shame, panic, dissociation, or compulsive checking. If those harms increase, the practice should be revised or retired for solo use.","result":"Pending.","impact":"pending","next_action":"Add stop criteria, exclusion criteria, and a brief distress scale to any pilot of the practice.","status":"proposed"}]}
